[2026-07-09 14:30:38] ŌåÆ 22501535027310: What you and I discussed in the car is this:

* Product investments can be made on a spectrum: from *founder gut* to *market research validated* (with *seller/customer/field signaled* somewhere in between)
* ŌüĀFounder Gut type decisions are cheap to make, Market Research Validated ones are expensive.
* ŌüĀThere are costs to getting the decision wrong: 
* ŌüĀ1. Opportunity cost of not building something else that is known to be needed
* ŌüĀ2. GTM orgŌĆÖs investment in taking the product to market
* ŌüĀ3. Culture impact of not winning when product doesnŌĆÖt find PMF
* ŌüĀIn our situation, I suspect (not certain, but suspect) that we donŌĆÖt have cost #1 because every ŌĆ£goodŌĆØ idea that we all believe is worthwhile is being funded and built.  For example, if we didnŌĆÖt build any W365/Intune functionality, what would be build instead?  I donŌĆÖt think anyone knows.  We havenŌĆÖt said ŌĆ£noŌĆØ to some other high potential product in favor of W365/Intune and are now regretting doing it.  So my point is that the true cost of ŌĆ£moving fastŌĆØ and launching products based on ŌĆ£founder gutŌĆØ validation side of the spectrum is not costing us that much.  On the contrary, it could be saving us time/money by not going through formal market research to validate every possible idea before building it.
* ŌüĀIf the above is true, the question of where should we be investing on the product side comes in.  We can invest in enhancing AVD functionality, which not only are we already doing, but there is probably not much more we need to invest to win business.  We can also invest in promising new product ideas and concepts, like weŌĆÖre doing with W365, Intune, etc.
* ŌüĀThe true cost shifts to GTM.  Taking a product to market and not finding PMF sucks.  GTM team should be finding the shortest path to ARR.  This means favoring PMF-validated products over new ones, as long as the TAM hasnŌĆÖt been exhausted.
* ŌüĀSelling AVD used to be easy.  Microsoft would pull us in, we didnŌĆÖt have competition, there was no W365 to position against, customers who really needed us had no options.  Win rates were very high.
* ŌüĀIt became much harder.  AVD isnŌĆÖt growing as fast, W365 is the hero motion, many customers already have Nerdio, Microsoft isnŌĆÖt excited about us any longer, this all leads to shrinking win rates.  
* ŌüĀI suspect the sales team is expecting an ŌĆ£easy saleŌĆØ by picking up ŌĆ£low hanging fruitŌĆØ customers, which was the case with AVD for a while and is no longer the case.  They have the climb the tree much higher.  Therefore, they are looking to product to hand them another magic product that will make selling as easy as AVD used to be.  IŌĆÖd love to do that and we have been trying, but no luck so far.
* ŌüĀSo what does that practically mean?  I think LarryŌĆÖs framework is the right way to look at it.  Define all the motions, score them on a dimension like Win Rate, compare them to each other and decide where to put the bets.  To me it looks like AVD should be getting disproportionate amount of investment on GTM, product should continue building the products that we have customer-validated to be needed and Sales should be experimenting and perfecting selling those products while feeding Product with the intel they need to make them even better.

Do you agree with the above?
